The Agentic SEC Filing Analyst was designed to demonstrate a complete agentic workflow—planning, tool use, autonomy, grounding, and self‑evaluation—applied to a realistic financial analysis task. SEC filings are an ideal domain because they require multi‑step reasoning, retrieval from external systems, structured extraction, reconciliation of inconsistent segment names, KPI computation, and narrative synthesis. A single LLM call cannot handle this complexity; the workflow naturally demands an agent that can plan, call tools, recover from failures, and revise its outputs. Each tool in the system—such as search_filings, extract_text, segment_stitcher, and compute_kpis—was intentionally designed to isolate a specific capability the agent needs to complete the end‑to‑end analysis.
The system prompt, agent loop, and self‑evaluation mechanism were chosen to enforce structure, prevent hallucination, and ensure high‑quality outputs. The agent is instructed to plan before acting, ground all numbers in extracted data, and revise its memo when evaluation scores fall below a threshold. Streamlit was selected for deployment because it provides a transparent, interactive interface that makes the agent’s reasoning and tool calls observable—an important requirement for agentic system evaluation. Overall, the architecture reflects deliberate design choices that balance autonomy, reliability, and financial domain expertise, demonstrating both technical understanding and intellectual ownership of the system.
